Music Genre Classification

Based on Song Sentiment

Aleksandra Gawor, Paulina KuÅ‚akowska

1. Introduction

1.1. Research questions

In this paper we aim to utilize text mining, NLP and sentimental analysis to mine for patterns in associating the sentiments within a song with its genre. Is it possible to associate the mood of a song with the genre? Are some words more popular for a certain genre and appear more frequently? Is it possible to predict the genre basing only on the sentiment of a song and its lyrics?

1.2. Literature overview

The field of Natural Language Processing in music has emerged to improve automatic tools for music classification and recommendation. Most of research for classyfying the genre based on mood of a song used features like the sentiment of songâ€™s lyrics, but also audio features, which we lack in our analysis.

2. Methodology

In our analysis we focused solely on processing the lyrics of songs and extracting the polarity, and proportions of words negative vs.Â positive to use them later as features for predicting the genre of a song. Th implemented Machine Learning method was the Support Vector Machine (SVM) algorithm, which is a popular tool in text mining and sentimental analysis, also known as good for dealing with multiclass classification. We would like to classify about 10 classes, i.e.Â 10 different music genres, using sentiment charactersitics of songs lyrics.

2.1. Data set

For the sake of analysis, we used Kaggleâ€™s dataset 380,000+ lyrics from MetroLyrics. The initial data consisted of 339277 observations of 6 variables. Our dataset is a sample of 20000 rows.

The first step was to draw a sample from our data and remove subspaces that were included in our data set.

Then, we did a tokenization, which breaks the text into individual tokens and transforms it into a data structure, in our case, unnested into a wordâ€“i.e.Â extracting words from lyrics.

lyrics <- lyrics %>% unnest_tokens(word, lyrics)

After tokenization it was time to remove all weird characters from the newly created â€œwordâ€ column.
Because some songs included special or foreign language characters there was a need to get rid of them. Also, we needed to exclude some typical for lyrics phrases, like â€œchorusâ€, â€œverseâ€ etc. and lyrics ornaments such as â€œlalaâ€, â€œoohâ€, â€œyeahâ€ that do not have any meaning.

lyrics <- lyrics %>%

3. Classification

3.1. Extracting polarity

Before classfication we would like to extract polarity and positive/negative proportion features that are going to be used in the model. We used the spread() function to separate the sentiments into columns and mutate() to create a polarity (positive - negative) feature (Liske, 2018).

# Positive / negative ratios and polarity 

lyrics_bing <- lyrics %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"))
## Joining, by = "word"
lyrics_polarity <- lyrics_bing %>%
  count(sentiment, song) %>%
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(polarity = positive - negative,
         percent_positive = positive / (positive + negative) * 100,
         percent_negative = negative / (positive + negative) * 100)

# we only need 'genre' variable as well
lyrics_genre <- lyrics %>% select(c("song", "genre"))

# drop duplicates (we are interested in whole song, not observations for each word)
lyrics_song <- unique(lyrics_genre)

# now we are ready to combine the two sets of variables
lyrics_set <- merge(lyrics_song, lyrics_polarity, by = "song")

# we set the genre to factor, to read it as a response variable
lyrics_set$genre <- as.factor(lyrics_set$genre)

Genre polarity and sentiment visualization:

# Genre polarity visualization 
lyrics_set %>%
  ggplot( aes(genre, polarity, fill = genre)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "red") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11)) +
  theme_bw()+

  ggtitle("Polarity by Genre")

3.2. Support Vector Machine

The used method was the Support Vector Machine with radial kernel and 10 predicted classes. We trained the model according to the given formula on the train set and validated the predictions on the test set. The results are visible in the confusion matrix.

set.seed(123456)
training_obs <- createDataPartition(lyrics_set$genre, 
                                    p = 0.7, 
                                    list = FALSE) 
lyrics.train <- lyrics_set[training_obs,]
lyrics.test  <- lyrics_set[-training_obs,]

# Defining the model formula and training the model
svm.model <- svm(genre ~ negative + positive + polarity + percent_positive + percent_negative, 
                 data = lyrics.train)

summary(svm.model)

The algorithm fails to predict certain genres. Its accuracy is rather low (43%), and it only classifies the most representative in terms of number of songs genres correctly, and classifies other types as one of them as well. The reason is high difference in our data distribution and scarcity of songs for other than Hip-Hop, Pop or Rock music.

3.3. Results and conclusions

The sentimental analysis of words provided us some interesting relationships when it comes to genre of a song and its lyricsâ€™ sentiments. We were able to observe some most frequent words within distinct music genres, and the genresâ€™prevailing sentiments. Unfortnately, however, we were not able to make prediction that would classify the genre of a song correctly, basing of a songâ€™s polarity. What could be done to improve the model is for example up-sampling to balance the data while using only the most common genres together with some tuning. What is more, there could be a very low variability of our data when it comes to polarity, and most genres may be simply too similar or neutral in sentiment. An even better idea would be to scrap more songs for bigger representation of scarce genres and balance the proportions in our dataset.
